    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Keyword research</strong> is the process of finding, analysing, and prioritising the search terms people type into search engines. It reveals what your audience is looking for, the monthly volume of that demand, how competitive each query is, and what content format (guide, list, product page, video) searchers expect. Ahrefs analysed 1 billion pages and found that 96.55% get zero organic traffic from Google — the primary cause is targeting keywords nobody searches for, or that the site can't competitively rank for.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Primary tools</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Ahrefs, Semrush, GSC</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Keyword Research</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Refresh cadence</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Quarterly</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Publishing content without keyword research is guessing at what your audience wants. Ahrefs' billion-page study proves the result: most content gets no traffic, because most content wasn't built around what people actually search for. Keyword research replaces guesswork with data.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is keyword research?</h2>
        <p>Keyword research is market research for search. Instead of surveying customers about what they want, you use search data to see exactly what questions people ask, what problems they're trying to solve, and what products they're comparing — before you write a single word of content.</p>
        <p>It produces four outputs that drive every downstream SEO decision:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Search terms</strong> — the exact phrases people type into Google</li>
          <li><strong>Search volume</strong> — how many times per month that phrase is searched</li>
          <li><strong>Keyword difficulty</strong> — how competitive it is to rank on page 1</li>
          <li><strong>Search intent</strong> — what the searcher is trying to do (learn, compare, buy, navigate)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Together, these four signals tell you whether a keyword is worth targeting, how much effort it requires, and what type of content Google will reward for that query.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why intent matters more than volume</div>
          <p>"CRM pricing" gets 800 monthly searches. "What is a CRM" gets 12,000. But a business selling CRM software should prioritise "CRM pricing" — the searcher is close to buying. Intent alignment between the content and the searcher's goal is the single most important keyword selection criterion after basic search volume viability.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why keyword research matters for every content decision</h2>
        <p>Every piece of content on your site should have a keyword research foundation. Here's why:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Prevents wasted effort.</strong> A 30-article content sprint targeting keywords nobody searches for produces zero organic traffic. A single well-researched keyword list prevents months of unproductive work.</li>
          <li><strong>Reveals buyer intent signals.</strong> Keyword research shows you when people are ready to buy ("best accounting software for freelancers") vs. when they're learning ("how does accounting software work"). This determines content type and CTA placement.</li>
          <li><strong>Uncovers competitor gaps.</strong> Analysing which keywords competitors rank for — and you don't — produces a direct content roadmap without any guesswork about topics.</li>
          <li><strong>Prioritises the content backlog.</strong> Most teams have more content ideas than capacity. Keyword data (volume × difficulty × intent value) creates an objective ranking of what to write first.</li>
          <li><strong>Informs site structure.</strong> Keyword clusters — groups of related terms — define which topics need pillar pages, which need supporting articles, and how internal links should flow.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How keyword research works — the 4-step process</h2>
        <p>Effective keyword research follows a consistent four-step process regardless of the tool you use:</p>

        <h3>Step 1 — Generate seed keywords</h3>
        <p>Start with 5–10 broad terms that describe your business, product, or audience's problems. A payroll software company might use: "payroll," "employee pay," "salary software," "payroll processing," "HR payroll."</p>
        <p>Sources for seeds:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Your product/service categories</li>
          <li>Problems your customers describe in support tickets and sales calls</li>
          <li>Google's autocomplete and "People also ask" for queries you already rank for</li>
          <li>Competitor site structures and blog categories</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Step 2 — Expand with keyword tools</h3>
        <p>Input each seed into Ahrefs Keywords Explorer, Semrush Keyword Magic, or Google Keyword Planner. The tool returns:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Related keywords (variations, questions, comparisons)</li>
          <li>Monthly search volume (be aware: these are estimates, accurate to ±50% for many terms)</li>
          <li>Keyword difficulty score (0–100)</li>
          <li>SERP snapshot — what types of pages currently rank</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Step 3 — Analyse intent and competition</h3>
        <p>For each keyword that passes a basic volume threshold, open the actual SERP and assess:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Intent match</strong> — are ranking pages the same format you'd create?</li>
          <li><strong>Realistic competition</strong> — are rankings dominated by mega-sites you can't compete with, or mid-authority sites within reach?</li>
          <li><strong>SERP features</strong> — featured snippets, image packs, and video carousels reduce organic CTR even if you rank position 1</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Step 4 — Group, prioritise, and map</h3>
        <p>Cluster remaining keywords by topic and intent. For each cluster, identify the highest-value keyword as the primary target and the rest as secondary targets for the same page or supporting content. Then prioritise clusters by business value × achievability.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Types of keyword research</h2>

