          <span class="uf-comment"># Startup published 30 blog posts without research</span><br>
          All posts: 0 keyword targeting, chosen by gut feel<br>
          Result after 6 months: <span class="uf-old">47 total organic visits</span><br><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># After implementing keyword research:</span><br>
          Next 30 posts: researched, difficulty-matched, intent-aligned<br>
          Result after 6 months: <span class="uf-status">4,200 organic visits</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Keyword research vs keyword mapping — what comes first?</h2>
        <p>They're sequential, not alternatives. You can't map what you haven't researched.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Keyword research (phase 1)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Discovers which terms have search demand</li>
              <li>Evaluates difficulty and intent for each term</li>
              <li>Produces a prioritised keyword list</li>
              <li>Outcome: you know what to target</li>
              <li>Refresh: quarterly + event-triggered</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Keyword mapping (phase 2)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Assigns researched keywords to specific pages</li>
              <li>Prevents cannibalization across the site</li>
              <li>Guides title tags, H1s, and content structure</li>
              <li>Outcome: you know which page targets what</li>
              <li>Updated: every time a new page is published</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">8 best practices for keyword research in 2026</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Always check the actual SERP.</strong> Tool data tells you volume and difficulty. The SERP tells you what Google actually wants to show for that query. A blog post format vs. a product page vs. a Reddit thread — this determines your content type before you write a word.</li>
          <li><strong>Prioritise long-tail keywords for new sites.</strong> New sites (DR under 20) should build their initial keyword list from KD 0–20 long-tail terms. These rank faster, convert better, and build the topical authority needed for head terms later.</li>
          <li><strong>Don't ignore zero-volume keywords with clear intent.</strong> A keyword showing 0 searches/month in a tool may still get 50–100 searches monthly (tools round low volumes to zero). If the intent is highly specific and commercial, it's worth a page.</li>
          <li><strong>Use search volume as a tiebreaker, not the primary filter.</strong> First filter by intent fit, then KD vs. your domain authority, then search volume. Volume is the last criterion, not the first.</li>
          <li><strong>Map keywords before writing briefs.</strong> Assign every keyword to a URL in a spreadsheet before content production begins. This prevents two writers from independently creating competing articles.</li>
          <li><strong>Revisit research quarterly.</strong> Search trends change. New competitors publish content and claim keywords you'd targeted. Seasonal terms peak and trough. A quarterly refresh keeps your list current.</li>
          <li><strong>Mine your GSC data monthly.</strong> Google Search Console shows queries you already rank for (positions 11–50) that are close to page 1. These "near-miss" keywords are your fastest wins — a focused optimisation sprint often moves them in 4–6 weeks.</li>
          <li><strong>Build topical clusters, not isolated articles.</strong> Google rewards sites that demonstrate comprehensive coverage of a topic. A pillar page on "email marketing" supported by 8–12 cluster articles on related subtopics will outrank a single article targeting the head term.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — targeting head terms before building authority</div>
          <p>A new site targeting "project management software" (KD 78) before establishing domain authority through long-tail content will never rank for it. The common result: months of publishing with no organic traffic. The fix is a deliberate authority-building sequence — long-tail first, medium-difficulty second, head terms only once DR and topical authority support it.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common keyword research mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Relying on one tool only</strong> — each tool has different keyword databases and volume estimates. Cross-checking 2 tools reduces the risk of missing high-value terms or over-estimating volume.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring negative intent signals</strong> — "free CRM" searchers are not buyers. Mapping commercial pages to informational or price-sensitive keywords wastes crawl budget and produces zero conversions.</li>
          <li><strong>Not updating research after major algorithm updates</strong> — Google's ranking signals shift. A keyword that was KD 30 in 2024 may now feature a SERP dominated by mega-brands due to the 2025 Helpful Content emphasis. Re-evaluate after major updates.</li>
          <li><strong>Building keyword lists without volume floor</strong> — targeting hundreds of keywords with under 10 monthly searches each produces pages with essentially no organic opportunity. Set a minimum volume threshold (even 50/month) appropriate to your niche.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping competitor keyword analysis</strong> — foundational research from seed keywords alone misses a large share of keywords your competitors rank for. Always combine bottom-up seed expansion with top-down competitor analysis.</li>
        </ul>

